  "created": "2025-10-14",
  "description": "Yeast peroxisome biogenesis in *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* is a dynamic and highly regulated process essential for cellular metabolism, particularly fatty acid $\\beta$-oxidation. Initiated by environmental cues like fatty acids or oleate, or increased cellular metabolic demand, the process begins with the transcriptional activation of *PEX* genes and peroxisomal enzyme genes, often mediated by transcription factors like Oaf1/Pip2. Peroxisomes can arise *de novo* from specialized ER domains or by growth and division of existing peroxisomes. In the *de novo* pathway, Pex3 and Pex16 insert into the ER membrane, leading to the budding of pre-peroxisomal vesicles. Simultaneously, peroxisomal membrane proteins (PMPs) are synthesized on free ribosomes, chaperoned by Pex19, and delivered to either nascent pre-peroxisomes or existing peroxisomes for insertion. Matrix proteins, also synthesized on free ribosomes, bind to receptors (Pex5 for PTS1, Pex7 for PTS2) and are imported into the peroxisomal lumen via a docking complex involving Pex14, with the Pex2/10/12 RING complex facilitating receptor recycling. Following protein import, peroxisomes expand their membrane through lipid synthesis and import, elongate, and proliferate via fission, a process involving Pex11, Dnm1, and Vps1. Post-translational modifications further regulate peroxisome assembly, function, and turnover, ensuring cellular metabolic homeostasis.",
  "id": "yeast_yeast_peroxisome_biogenesis",
